I have a set of 100 integer solutions with D<1e27 to the Fermat 
quartic A^4+B^4+C^4=D^4, and I am trying to find more. Some of 
the solutions are connected by being on the same elliptic curve. 
I noticed a modular relationship between some sets of elliptic curves. 
Suggest ways to apply the Riemann surface viewpoint to explore these 
modular relationships that might lead to new elliptic curves and 
thus to new solutions.

Part of Answer from Perplexity.ai:
You can organize your curves by their \(j\)-invariant, conductor, 
and isogeny class, then ask whether the related torus parameters 
lie on special loci in the upper half-plane such as Hecke orbits 
or CM points. Curves with the same or closely related modular 
data may come from a shared parametrization, and that often signal
a hidden transformation that can generate new rational points.

Parts of answer from Gemini AI:
Because this specific surface (Fermat quartic) has the maximum 
possible Picard rank ($\rho = 20$ over $\mathbb{C}$), it is a 
"singular" K3 surface (in the sense of Shioda and Inose). These 
surfaces are inherently modular, and the Riemann surface viewpoint 
provides a geometric map to generate new solutions through the 
interplay of lattice theory and modular forms.

While a genus-1 curve (elliptic curve) is determined by its period 
$\tau \in \mathbb{H}$, a K3 surface is determined by its period 
matrix—the integrals of a unique holomorphic 2-form $\omega$ over 
the cycles of $H_2(X, \mathbb{Z})$.

For a singular K3 surface, the transcendental lattice $T_X$ (the 
part of the homology not represented by algebraic cycles) has 
rank 2. This lattice is isomorphic to a lattice $\Lambda$ 
in $\mathbb{C}$, which immediately associates the surface with 
a specific weight 3 modular form.

Shioda-Inose structure, which relates your K3 surface to the 
product of two elliptic curves $E_1 \times E_2$. New elliptic 
curves (fibrations) can be found by looking for different ways 
to embed a "frame" (a rank-2 lattice) into the Picard lattice 
of the surface.

The Automorphism Group: The Fermat quartic surface has a massive 
automorphism group (order 1536). Any solution $(A, B, C, D)$ 
you find can be acted upon by this group to produce others.

Mordell-Weil Lattices: Each elliptic fibration has a Mordell-Weil 
group of rational sections.

Strategy: If you have 100 solutions, check if they belong to 
different fibrations. A modular relationship between two fibrations 
suggests a correspondence (a 2-cycle in the product $X \times X$). 
By applying these correspondences (which act like Hecke operators), 
you can map a known solution on one curve to a potentially new 
solution on a different, "modularly related" curve.

Suggestions for Finding New Curves:

A. Identify the Transcendental Lattice Calculate the Gram matrix 
of the transcendental lattice $T_X$. For the Fermat quartic, it 
is known to be $\begin{pmatrix} 8 & 0 \\ 0 & 8 \end{pmatrix}$. 
This lattice corresponds to the modular form $\eta(4z)^6$.Action: 
Check if the Fourier coefficients $a_p$ of this modular form 
correlate with the number of solutions you find modulo $p$. 
This can "predict" the existence of solutions in higher ranges.

B. Use the "Hecke Correspondence" on the Surface. Just as modular 
curves $X_0(N)$ have Hecke operators $T_p$, the Picard lattice 
of a K3 surface allows for algebraic correspondences. Action: 
If two curves $E_1$ and $E_2$ are modularly related (e.g., 
their $j$-invariants satisfy a modular equation 
$\Phi_n(j_1, j_2) = 0$), there is a geometric map between them. 
Apply this map to your known rational points on $E_1$ to see 
if they land on rational points on $E_2$.

C. Search for "Modular Points" in the Period Domain
The moduli space of these elliptic curves can be viewed as a 
curve (often a modular curve itself) embedded in the larger 
moduli space of the K3 surface.

Action: Identify the CM points (Complex Multiplication) on 
your elliptic curves. On a singular K3 surface, the curves 
appearing in fibrations often have CM. New curves can be 
discovered by finding other points in the period domain that
share the same transcendental lattice properties.

Check if the conductors of the elliptic curves you've 
